 very popular. Among the most famous works of Gaudi\'s Sagrada Familia also include Park Guell, La Pedrera on Passeig de Gracia and Casa Batllo.\n\nWorld Heritage Site by UNESCO since 1984, the Park Guell is one of the most visited places in the city. From its terrace one has a beautiful view. If you like parks visit the Park of Montjuic and take the cable car to its summit.\n\nFootball fans will not want to miss a game at the Nou Camp stadium, or at least visit the stadium and museum.\n\nThe cost for most of these attractions is between 6 and 10 Euros. Note that the entrance to Parc Guell is free.','Youth Hostel - Barcelona attractions ','','inherit','open','open','','408-autosave','','','2010-09-10 07:22:43','2010-09-10 06:22:43','',408,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/408-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(1618,1,'2010-06-24 23:48:27','2010-06-24 22:48:27','<img class=\"size-full wp-image-343 alignleft\" title=\"Plaza Real Barcelone\" src=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/IMG_2602-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Plaza Real Barcelone\" width=\"225\" height=\"169\" />\r\n\r\nSecond city of Spain, prosperous and vibrant, the capital of the province of Catalonia covers about 490 square kilometres with 1.5 million people. Located along the Mediterranean coast, it is a major Spanish center not only for its economic but also cultural and touristic boldness.\r\nThe two languages commonly spoken in Barcelona are the Castilian (Spanish) and Catalan. The signs and posters are written in Catalan, but if you talk to people in Spanish, they will respond in that language. The currency is the Euro.\r\n<h3>Arriving and moving around Barcelona</h3>\r\nWe move around in Barcelona by metro, bus or taxi. The most simple and practical means of transport is the subway, which lets visitors reach some outlying attractions such as Park Guell.\r\nInstead of buying individual tickets, if you intend to take the subway several times in the same day, it is more economical to purchase a tourist pass for several days. In addition, these cards are valid in buses as well as the subway. You can also buy the tickets by 10, which is cheaper than per unit.\r\nIn downtown, the Gothic Quarter is usually and easily visited on foot, as is Las Ramblas.  The climate of Barcelona will not force you to lock yourself too often to seek protection from the rain.','Barcelona','Second city of Spain, prosperous and vibrant, the capital of the province of Catalonia covers about 490 square kilometres with 1.5 million people. Located along the Mediterranean coast, it is a major Spanish center not only for its economic but also cultural and touristic boldness.\r\nThe two languages commonly spoken in Barcelona are the Castilian (Spanish) and Catalan. The signs and posters are written in Catalan, but if you talk to people in Spanish, they will respond in that language. The currency is the Euro.','inherit','open','open','','398-revision-19','','','2010-06-24 23:48:27','2010-06-24 22:48:27','',398,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/398-revision-19/',0,'revision','',0),(421,1,'2010-03-03 20:12:28','2010-03-03 20:12:28','Il faut bien quelques jours pour visiter l’ensemble des attractions de Barcelone, et se promener dans ses divers quartiers. \r\nLe monument le plus important de Barcelone est sans aucun doute la Sagrada Familia, une des nombreuses oeuvres d’Antonio Gaudi disséminées dans la ville (14 en tout). La marque de cet architecte sur Barcelone est importante et ses travaux ont contribué à rendre Barcelone très populaire. Parmi les oeuvres les plus connues de Gaudi, outre la Sagrada Familia, on peut citer le Parc Guell, La Pedrera sur le Passeig de Gracia et la Casa Batllo. \r\nInscrit au Patrimoine mondial de l’UNESCO depuis 1984, le Parc Guell est un des lieux les plus visités de la ville. Depuis sa terrasse on a une vue superbe. Si vous aimez les parcs, allez aussi visiter le parc de Montjüic, et prenez le téléphérique pour monter à son sommet.\r\nLes amateurs 