 années 1970, sous l\'impulsion du président Georges Pompidou. Son architecture à l\'époque révolutionnaire fait maintenant partie intégrante de l\'image de Paris.\n\nLa vocation de cet espace est de regrouper et de mettre à la disposition du public différentes formes de culture et d\'art contemporain, que ce soit la musique, les arts graphiques, le design ou les livres.\n\nLe centre Pompidou héberge d\'ailleurs une des plus riches bibliothèques publiques, qui selon l\'idée du président Pompidou, devait attirer les visiteurs qui ensuite auraient accès aux autres richesses culturelles offertes par le centre. De nombreuses expositions sont régulièrement organisées, ne manquez pas de passer quelques heures dans ce centre lors de votre séjour.\n\n<h3>Pour s\'y rendre</h3>\nLe Centre Pompidou est situé dans le quatrième arrondissement de Paris, tout près des Halles. Il est facilement accessible par différents moyens de transport.\nRambuteau sur la ligne 11 est la station de métro la plus proche. Les stations Hôtel de Ville et Châtelet sont également assez proche de Beaubourg, ainsi que la station de RER: Châtelet - Les Halles. Plusieurs bus circulent aussi dans les environs.\n\nIl est ouvert tous les jours sauf le mardi. Le musée et les expositions sont accessibles de 11h à 21h. Il peut y avoir des horaires différents pour les événements spéciaux.\nLa Bibliothèque Publique d\'information, la BPI, est ouverte du lundi au vendredi (sauf le mardi) de 12h à 22h, et en fin de semaine de 11h à 22h. \n\nPour ce qui est des tarifs d\'entrée, les prix sont variables selon ce à quoi vous voulez accéder. Il est possible d\'acheter vos billets d\'avance, en ligne.\n\nLe Centre Pompidou de Paris fait partie des musées qui sont accessibles par le biais du Paris Museum pass. Ce pass qui s\'adresse aux mordus de musées donne un accès rapide à 60 musées et monuments de Paris et de l\'Ile de France pour des tarifs allant de 32 € pour 2 jours  à 64 € pour 6 jours.\n\nEt si vous voulez séjourner dans le quartier du Centre Pompidou, <a href=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/auberges/recherche/France/Paris\">voyez notre sélection d\'auberges et petits hôtels</a> et faites votre réservation en ligne!','Centre Pompidou','','inherit','open','open','','555-revision','','','2010-03-12 03:50:41','2010-03-12 03:50:41','',555,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/555-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(562,1,'2010-03-12 03:22:15','2010-03-12 03:22:15','<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-525\" title=\"Paris\" src=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/IMG_7002-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Le Louvre\" width=\"217\" height=\"162\" />\"Paris, reine du monde…\" La réputation internationale de la capitale de la France n’est plus à faire, Paris est une des destinations les plus prisées au monde, et pour de nombreuses raisons.\r\n\r\nParis couvre plus de 500 000 km2 et, elle est habitée par plus de 2 millions de personnes (presque 12 millions si on compte les banlieues environnantes).\r\n\r\nOn y parle français, et la monnaie en vigueur est l’Euro.\r\n<h3 style=\"clear: both;\">Transport</h3>\r\n<strong>En arrivant à Paris</strong>\r\n\r\nParis a deux grands aéroports, Orly et Charles de Gaulle, aussi connu sous le nom de Roissy. On peut rejoindre le centre ville de Paris facilement grâce aux bus. L’Orlybus se rend à la place Denfert-Rocherau et le  Roissybus dessert la station de métro Opéra . Depuis Orly il est aussi possible de prendre le métro qui s’appelle Orlyval.\r\n\r\n<strong>Dans Paris</strong>\r\n\r\nParis est une grande ville, et pour vous rendre d’un point à un autre vous aurez probablement besoin d’emprunter les transports en communs: bus, métro, RER . La société qui gère les transports à Paris s’appelle la RATP.\r\n\r\nPrendre le métro peut être désagréable aux heures de pointe, mais cela peut aussi faire l’objet même d’une visite, tant certaines stations sont belles. Ne manquez pas les stations suivantes :  Abbesses, Arts-et-Métiers, Palais-Royal et Pont Neuf.\r\n\r\nOn peut aussi découvrir Paris en bateau, le long de la Seine. Par beau temps, il vous faudra absolument vous promener à vélo. Le système de location avec des bornes dans toute la ville, le Vélib, est parfait. Et bien sûr, il faut marcher!\r\n\r\nSi vous comptez visiter beaucoup de quartiers de Paris en quelques jours, il est recommandé de prendre le forfait offert par la RATP, le Paris Visite. Ce forfait est  valable 1, 2, 3 ou 5 jours consécutifs, sur les zones 1 à 3 ou 1 à 6, et coûte de 9 à 50 euros, dépendamment de la formule que vous choisissez. Il existe d’autres formules adaptés à tous les besoins, renseignez vous à un guichet de la RATP dès votre arrivée pour économiser le plus possible. Le Métro de Paris est très développé et vous permettra d’accéder à tous les points d’intérêt assez rapidement\r\n\r\nÀ moins que vous ayez une bonne connaissance de Paris, ou un copilote efficace, évitez de vous y déplacer en voiture.\r\n\r\n<h3>Logement à Paris</h3>\r\nDe la simple auberge à l\'hôtel cinq étoiles en passant par le bed & breakfast, il y en a pour tous les goûts et toutes les bourses à Paris. \r\nVous trouverez sur notre site (dans le menu de droite) une sélection des auberges de jeunesse et autres types de logement les plus recommandés dans divers quartiers de Paris. Un simple clic vous permettra de faire une réservation! \r\nPour voir la liste complète des auberges et faire votre réservation, <a href=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/auberges/recherche/France/Paris\">accédez à notre liste</a>.','Paris','La réputation internationale de la capitale de la France n’est plus à faire, Paris est une des destinations les plus prisées de France et même au monde, et pour de nombreuses raisons. \r\nVous trouverez dans ces pages quelques pistes et notre sélection des meilleurs auberges de jeunesse pour organiser votre séjour à Paris.','inherit','open','open','','524-revision-12','','','2010-03-12 03:22:15','2010-03-12 03:22:15','',524,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/524-revision-12/',0,'revision','',0),(563,1,'2010-09-14 06:14:34','2010-09-14 05:14:34','<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-560\" title=\"pompidou2\" src=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/pompidou2-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Centre Georges Pompidou à Paris\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />The Centre Pompidou, also known as Beaubourg, was constructed in the 1970s under the leadership of President Georges Pompidou. Its architecture, which was revolutionary at the time,  is now part of the image of Paris.\n\nThe purpose of this space is to consolidate and make available various forms of public culture, such as contemporary art, music, and graphic art and design.\n\nThe Centre Pompidou also hosts a rich public library. It was built to attract and impress visitors, and give them an understanding of the cultural richness offered by the center, and by Paris. Many exhibitions are held here regularly. Do not forget to spend a few hours at the Centre Pompidou during your stay in Paris.\n<h3>To get there</h3>\nThe Centre Pompidou is located in the fourth arrondissement of Paris, near Les Halles. It is easily accessible by various means of transport.\nRambuteau on line 11 is the nearest subway station. The Station Hotel de Ville or Châtelet are also fairly close to Beaubourg and the RER: Châtelet - Les Halles. Several buses are also circulating nearby.\n\nIt is open every day except on Tuesday. The museum and the exhibitions are open from 11Am to 9pm. There may be different schedules for special events.\nThe Bibliothèque Publique d\'information (BPI) is open Monday to Friday (except Tuesday) from noon to 10PM and on weekends from 11AM to 10PM.\n\nRegarding admission fees, prices vary depending on what you want to see. It is possible to buy tickets online in advance.\n\nThe Centre Pompidou in Paris is one of the museums that are accessible through the Paris Museum Pass. This pass, which is for enthusiasts of museums, gives quick access to 60 museums and monuments in Paris and Ile de France with rates ranging from 32 € for 2 days at 64 € for 6 days.\n\nAnd if you want to stay in the neighborhood of the Centre Pompidou, see our selection of <strong>youth hostels</strong> and small hotels.','Centre Pompidou','The Centre Pompidou, also known as Beaubourg, was constructed in the 1970s under the leadership of President Georges Pompidou. Its architecture, which was revolutionary at the time, is now part of the image of Paris.','inherit','open','open','','555-autosave','','','2010-09-14 06:14:34','2010-09-14 05:14:34','',555,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/555-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(1949,1,'2010-06-26 00:14:50','2010-06-25 23:14:50','<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-560\" title=\"pompidou2\" src=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/pompidou2-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Centre Georges Pompidou à Paris\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />The Centre Pompidou, also known as Beaubourg, was constructed n the 1970s under the leadership of President Georges Pompidou. Its architecture, which was revolutionary at the time,  is now part of the image of Paris.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this space is to consolidate and make available various forms of public culture as contemporary art, music, graphic arts, design or books.\r\n\r\nThe Centre Pompidou also hosts one of the richest public libraries, according to the idea that President Pompidou had to attract visitors who would then have access to other cultural richness offered by the center. Many exhibitions are held regularly, do not forget to spend a few hours at the centre Pompidou during your stay in Paris.\r\n<h3>To get there</h3>\r\nThe Centre Pompidou is located in the fourth arrondissement of Paris, near Les Halles. It is easily accessible by various means of transport.\r\nRambuteau on line 11 is the nearest subway station. The Station Hotel de Ville or Châtelet are also fairly close to Beaubourg and the RER: Châtelet - Les Halles. Several buses are also circulating nearby.\r\n\r\nIt is open every day except on Tuesday. The museum and the exhibitions are open from 11Am to 9pm. There may be different schedules for special events.\r\nThe Bibliothèque Publique d\'information (BPI) is open Monday to Friday (except Tuesday) from noon to 10PM and on weekends from 11AM to 10PM.\r\n\r\nRegarding admission fees, prices vary depending on what you want to see. It is possible to buy tickets in advance, online.\r\n\r\nThe Centre Pompidou in Paris is one of the museums that are accessible through the Paris Museum Pass. This pass, which is for enthusiasts of museums, gives quick access to 60 museums and monuments in Paris and Ile de France for rates ranging from 32 € for 2 days at 64 € for 6 days.\r\n\r\nAnd if you want to stay in the neighborhood of the Centre Pompidou, see our selection of hostels and small hotels and book online!','Centre Pompidou','The Centre Pompidou, also known as Beaubourg, was constructed n the 1970s under the leadership of President Georges Pompidou. Its architecture, which was revolutionary at the time,  is now part of the image of Paris.','inherit','open','open','','555-revision-6','','','2010-06-26 00:14:50','2010-06-25 23:14:50','',555,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/555-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(1670,1,'2010-06-24 17:43:06','2010-06-24 16:43:06','<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-560\" title=\"pompidou2\" src=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/pompidou2-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"Centre Georges Pompidou à Paris\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" />The Centre Pompidou, also known as Beaubourg, was born in the 1970s under the leadership of President Georges Pompidou. Its architecture, which was the revolutionary,  is now part of the image of Paris.\r\n\r\nThe purpose of this space is to consolidate and make available various forms of public culture as contemporary art, music, graphic arts, design or books.\r\n\r\nThe Centre Pompidou also hosts one of the richest public libraries, according to the idea that President Pompidou had to attract visitors who would then have access to other cultural richness offered by the center. Many exhibitions are held regularly, do not forget to spend a few hours at Le centre Pompidou during your stay in Paris.\r\n<h3>To get there</h3>\r\nThe Pompidou Center is located in the fourth arrondissement of Paris, near Les Halles. It is easily accessible by various means of transport.\r\nRambuteau on line 11 is the station nearest you. The Station Hotel de Ville or Châtelet are also fairly close to Beaubourg, and the RER: Châtelet - Les Halles. Several buses are also circulating nearby.\r\n\r\nIt is open every day except on Tuesday. The museum and the exhibitions are open from 11Am to 9pm. There may be different schedules for special events.\r\nThe Bibliothèque Publique d\'information (BPI) is open Monday to Friday (except Tuesday) from noon to 10PM and on weekends from 11AM to 10PM.\r\n\r\nRegarding admission fees, prices vary depending on what you want to see. It is possible to buy tickets in advance, online.\r\n\r\nThe Centre Pompidou in Paris is oneof the museums that are accessible through the Paris Museum Pass. This pass, which is for enthusiasts of museums, gives quick access to 60 museums and monuments in Paris and Ile de France for rates ranging from 32 € for 2 days at 64 € for 6 days.\r\n\r\nAnd if you want to stay in the neighborhood of the Centre Pompidou, see our selection of inns and small hotels and book online!<a href=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/auberges/recherche/France/Paris\"></a>','Centre Pompidou','','inherit','open','open','','555-revision-5','','','2010-06-24 17:43:06','2010-06-24 16:43:06','',555,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/555-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(660,4,'2010-07-06 07:00:54','2010-07-06 06:00:54','<img class=\"alignleft size-medium wp-image-528\" title=\"notredame\" src=\"http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/wp-content/uploads/2010/03/notredame-225x300.jpg\" alt=\"Cathédrale de Notre Dame de Paris\" width=\"225\" height=\"300\" />\n\nThere is so much to see and do in Paris ... Parks, monuments, museums, restaurants, whatever your taste is, you will find your happiness.\n\nHere are some ideas for sights that we present in this guide:\n\n- The Louvre Museum\n- Tour Eiffel, the biggest attraction of Paris\n- Montmartre, the Place du Tertre and the Sacred Heart\n- The Cathedral of Notre Dame\n- The Champs Elysees and Arc de Triomphe\n- The Sewers of Paris\n- Luxembourg Garden\n- The Musée d\'Orsay\n- Centre Georges Pompidou, which houses the largest collection of contemporary art in Europe.\n- Pere Lachaise Cemetery\n- The covered\n... And much more!\n\nBut beyond all these monuments and famous spots in the city of light, what is needed to tame this city is to walk again and again, and soak up the atmosphere of the various parts of the city.\n\nParis attractions mentioned above are mostly available for less than 10 euros, some are of course also free, such as parks, churches and cathedrals, walkways or the Père Lachaise. But beware of the many temptations where to spend throughout your walks, it is sometimes hard to resist!','Youth Hostel - Paris Attractions','','inherit','open','open','','527-autosave','','','2010-07-06 07:00:54','2010-07-06 06:00:54','',527,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/527-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(661,4,'2010-03-16 02:52:19','2010-03-16 01:52:19','Texte pour la page de contact\r\n<h3>Formulaire en ligne</h3>','Nous Joindre','','inherit','open','open','','655-revision-2','','','2010-03-16 02:52:19','2010-03-16 01:52:19','',655,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/655-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(662,1,'2010-03-16 05:42:38','2010-03-16 04:42:38','<h2>How and what information do we collect from our users?</h2>\r\nWe collect personal information from users when they register online and purchase online. Generally, this information includes a name, an e-mail address, a mailing address and the information contained in the credit card transaction when purchasing products.\r\n\r\nPersonal information provided to us by you is fully encrypted and protected (SSL). This information will never be shared, rented or sold to any third party individual or company.\r\n<h2>How do we use this information?</h2>\r\nThis information is used solely for internal marketing purposes. We do not sell, exchange, or disclose your personal information (name, e-mail address, mailing address, credit card data, etc.). The information that you provide us, and identifies you personally, is not shared with third parties other than for billing and mailing purpose.\r\n\r\nWe only contact people who specifically have requested or opted to receive our free newsletters or who have purchased one of our products.\r\n<h2>What are cookies, clear GIFs and how do we use them?</h2>\r\nLike many other commercial sites, our site uses standard technology called \"cookies\" and \"clear GIFs (Graphics Interchange Format) to collect information about how our website is used.\r\n\r\nA cookie is a small data text file that a website saves on the hard drive of your computer (if your browser allows it), which can be found later to identify yourself to the website. Cookies are designed to help the website recognize a user\'s browser as a previous visitor, and to save and remember any preferences that may have been selected while navigating their site.\r\n\r\nA cookie cannot be read by any site other than the one that placed the cookie in the first place.  Also, a cookie cannot transmit computer viruses or capture personal information that may reside in your computer.\r\n\r\nSometimes we work with external partner service companies that employ clear GIFs to help us measure the effectiveness of advertising. Clear GIFs are tiny graphics (the size of a punctuation mark) that contain unique identifiers that help us monitor online activity. The main difference between cookies and clear GIFs is that the latter do not use or bear personal data, but merely track the traffic and behaviour of visitors to, from and within multiple websites.\r\n<h2>How do we protect your information?</h2>\r\nYour personal information is stored in a fully secured server.  This information is only accessible to associates who manage our distribution list of customers who wish to receive our newsletter emails.\r\n\r\nThe newsletters that we send you contain an unsubscribe link. You can remove yourself from our newsletter distribution list anytime by clicking on the unsubscribe link.\r\n\r\nThis charter may be amended any time at our discretion.  We will post updates to this page accordingly. The last revision to this charter was March 5, 2010.\r\n\r\nIf you have any questions or concerns regarding our privacy policy, please feel free to contact us.','Privacy policy','','publish','open','open','','privacy-policy','','','2010-07-06 07:12:56','2010-07-06 06:12:56','',0,'http://www.nofeeshostels.com/info/?page_id=662',0,'page','',0),(1764,1,'2010-07-05 22:15:21','2010-07-05 21:15:21','<h2>How and what information do we collect from our users?</h2>\r\nWe collect personal information from users when they register online and purchase online. Generally, this information includes a name, an e-mail address, a mailing address and the information contained in the credit card transaction when purchasing products.\r\n\r\nPersonal information provided to us by you is fully encrypted and protected (SSL). This information will never be shared, rented or sold to any third party individual or company.\r\n<h2>How do we use this information?</h2>\r\nThis information is used solely for internal marketing purposes. We do not sell, exchange, or disclose your personal information (name, e-mail address, mailing address, credit card data, etc.). The information that you provide us, and identifies you personally, is not shared with third parties other than for billing and mailin